The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, January 23, 2004 				 Uco to increase Tier two capital 
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT				 	 Shetty in Calcutta on Thursday. A Telegraph picture																								Calcutta, Jan. 22: Uco Bank plans to raise tier-II capital by another Rs 250-400 crore. It hopes to come up with a subordinated bond issue within the next three months to enhance its capital adequacy ratio of 13.27 per cent. 																								The company today announced a third-quarter net profit of Rs 134 crore compared with Rs 130 crore in the corresponding previous period.																								The bank also plans to increase its presence in the South East Asian countries by setting up representative offices in Malaysia and Indonesia.																								The operating profit of the bank has gone up 10.42 per cent to Rs 212 crore compared with Rs 192 crore in the previous year. The banks profit from treasury operations is down from Rs 104 crore to Rs 56 crore. 																								The gross non-performing asset of the bank stood at 7.22 per cent against 8.57 per cent last year. The net NPA ratio has come down to 4.06 per cent from 4.64 per cent in the previous year.																								Chairman and managing director V. P. Shetty said, We would like to expand to Malaysia and Indonesia as we have offices in Singapore and Hong Kong. Initially, we may not go for full fledged branches and instead open representative offices.																								The bank was also in final stages of negotiations for agency arrangement with banks and exchange houses in Gulf countries for remittances to India. The banks total business stood at Rs 51,498 crore in December divided into deposits of Rs 33,415 crore and advances of Rs 18,083 crore. 
